   <standOff>
      <listPerson>
         <person xml:id="person_269">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Luigi</forename>
               <surname>Galvani</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1737"/>
            <death when="1798"/>
            <note>Italian surgeon and anatomist who carried out experiments with electricity and animals. The term 'galvanism' was named after him</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_199">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Alessandro</forename>
               <surname>Volta</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1745"/>
            <death when="1827"/>
            <note>Professor of experimental physics at the University of Pavia. At the end of the eighteenth century he Invented the Voltaic pile which produced electric current and which Davy shortly dubbed the battery. Davy described meeting him in 1814 in notebook 14/I, p.38. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_124">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Francis</forename>
               <surname>Bacon</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1561"/>
            <death when="1626"/>
            <note>English lawyer, politician and natural philosopher. His influential writings encouraged experimentation and the use of induction in investigating the natural world. He also recommended establishing institutions to promote collaborative research. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_036">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Isaac</forename>
               <surname>Newton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1642"/>
            <death when="1727"/>
            <note>Prominent English natural philosopher and mathematician greatly admired by Davy who once under the influence of several litres of nitrous oxide wrote in his notebook 'Davy &amp; Newton' in one inch letters. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_325">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Johann Georg</forename>
               <surname>Sulzer</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1720"/>
            <death when="1799"/>
            <note>Swiss mathematician who later worked in Berlin on electricity and also translated Hume into German.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_026">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Henry</forename>
               <surname>Cavendish</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1731"/>
            <death when="1810"/>
            <note>A central figure in English natural philosophy and chemistry, among other research he determined the density of the earth and discovered what would later be named hydrogen. He was one of the people who helped appoint Davy to the Royal Institution. Following his death in 1810 Davy delivered a widely-quoted eulogy on Cavendish and later arranged for some of his apparatus to be transferred to the Royal Institution. FRSL. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_317">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Paul</forename>
               <surname>Erman</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1764"/>
            <death when="1851"/>
            <note>German physician and physicist. He was mainly interested in electricity and magnetism and was the first recipient of the Volta Prize. ForMemRSL.</note>
         </person>
      </listPerson>
      <listAnnotation type="miscellaneous">
         <note xml:id="misc_228" type="description">
            <term id="misc_228-term">Voltaism</term>
            <gloss id="misc_228-gloss" target="#misc_228-term">
               <p>The production of an electric current by the chemical action of a liquid on metals, galvanism as produced by Volta's methods' (OED Online)</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_810" type="description">
            <term id="misc_810-term">Silk</term>
            <gloss id="misc_810-gloss" target="#misc_810-term">
               <p>A natural protein fibre formed by certain insects when they produce cocooons. </p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_130" type="description">
            <term id="misc_130-term">Leyden Jar</term>
            <gloss id="misc_130-gloss" target="#misc_130-term">
               <p>The Leyden Jar is an electrical component which stores a high-voltage electric charge between electrical conductors on the inside and outside of a glass jar.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_233" type="description">
            <term id="misc_233-term">torpedo</term>
            <gloss id="misc_233-gloss" target="#misc_233-term">
               <p>An electric ray fish.</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
         <note xml:id="misc_232" type="description">
            <term id="misc_232-term">gymnotus</term>
            <gloss id="misc_232-gloss" target="#misc_232-term">
               <p>Probably an electric eel, also known as the gynotus electricus or gymnotus electricus</p>
            </gloss>
         </note>
      </listAnnotation>
      <listNym type="chemical">
         <nym xml:id="chemical_201">
            <form>zinc</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Zn</p>
               <p>A a slightly brittle metal at room temperature and has a shiny-greyish appearance when oxidation is removed.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_070">
            <form>copper</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Cu</p>
               <p>A soft, malleable, and ductile metal with very high thermal and electrical conductivity. A freshly exposed surface of pure copper has a pinkish-orange colour.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_033">
            <form>quicksilver</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: Hg </p>
               <p>Mercury. A heavy, silvery element, mercury is the only metallic element that is known to be liquid at standard temperature and pressure.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_161">
            <form>voltaic</form>
            <def>
               <p>Refers to the current generated by voltaic pile, invented by Italian chemist Alessandro Volta.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_022">
            <form>oxygene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: O</p>
               <p>Now known as oxygen. Oxygen is a colourless, odourless, tasteless gas essential to living organisms.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_007">
            <form>hydrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: H</p>
               <p>Now known as hydrogen. Hydrogen is the lightest element and, at standard conditions, is a gas of diatomic molecules. It is colourless, odourless, tasteless, non-toxic, and highly combustible.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_037">
            <form>sulphur</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: S</p>
               <p>Pure sulphur is a tasteless, odourless, brittle solid that is pale yellow in colour, a poor conductor of electricity, and insoluble in water.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_151">
            <form>phosphorus</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: P</p>
               <p>A non-metallic chemical element of the nitrogen family. A colourless, semitransparent, soft, waxy solid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_030">
            <form>potash</form>
            <def>
               <p>An alkaline substance consisting largely of impure potassium carbonate. In October 1807, Davy decomposed potash using electricity, revealing the previously unknown element potassium.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_041">
            <form>boric acid</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: B(OH)3</p>
               <p>A compound of boron, oxygen, and hydrogen. Davy often refers to this as boracic acid.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_017">
            <form>nitrogene</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: N</p>
               <p>Now known as nitrogen. A colourless and odourless gas, nitrogen is non-combustible and non-toxic. Davy also refers to this as azote.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
         <nym xml:id="chemical_054">
            <form>carbon</form>
            <def>
               <p>Symbol/formula: C</p>
               <p>A non-metallic and tetravalent element. Well-known allotropes include graphite, diamond, amorphous carbon, and fullerenes.</p>
            </def>
         </nym>
      </listNym>
      <listBibl>
         <bibl xml:id="otherwork_179">
            <author>Francis Bacon</author>
            <title level="j">Of the Proficience and Advancement of Learning, Divine and Human</title>
            <date when="1605">1605</date>
            <note>Davy quotes from this text, popularly known as The Advancement of Learning. </note>
         </bibl>
      </listBibl>
   </standOff>
   <text>
      <body xml:lang="en">
         <div>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="1"
                xml:id="pb-1"
                facs="#i1"/>
            <lb/>
Lecture 1. Introductory<lb/>
to Electro Chemical Science<lb/>
March 12.<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">th</hi> 1808<lb/>
-- It affords me the most sincere pleasure to<lb/>
be able to appear again before you. - There is<lb/>
no desire more alive &amp; ardent in my mind than<lb/>
that of having it in my power to combine<lb/>
experiments made for the advancement of Science<lb/>
with the details of public lectures. ---<lb/>
-- The present course admits of such an union<lb/>
&amp; I shall consider my exertions &amp; labour in<lb/>
delivering it as more than compensated for<lb/>
by the satisfaction I shall receive if the end<lb/>
to which my wishes are so strongly directed be<lb/>
in any manner accomplished. --<lb/>
-- I speak of labour &amp; exertion not with<lb/>
the view of making a parade of difficulties &amp;<lb/>
of the merit of overcoming them but merely<lb/>
to prepare for &amp; to ask you to consider with<lb/>
indulgence what I am convinced will be a<lb/>
very imperfect work. ---<lb/>
-- The subject you will feel is in a great<lb/>
measure unexplored. - Little or no assistance<lb/>
in the investigation can be derived from Books<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
&amp; I am obliged to trust almost wholly, to<lb/>
my own efforts &amp; my own limited information<lb/>
Had I been able to make my preparations in<lb/>
full health &amp; in full time, I should have<lb/>
possessed more confidence; &amp; the novelty<lb/>
&amp; importance of the subject would have been<lb/>
sources rather of hope than of fear; but<lb/>
the long confinement &amp; severe illness which<lb/>
I have sustained have prevented me from<lb/>
maturely arranging my plans. Many ideas<lb/>
in full vividness before, I am unable at<lb/>
this moment to recover &amp; investigations have<lb/>
been left incomplete which I had hoped<lb/>
to be able now to bring before you, &amp; to<lb/>
connect with some brilliant results |_ You<lb/>
must regard this attempt, as an unfinished<lb/>
building of which the scaffolding has failed<lb/>
&amp; demands repair; unfinished, but not<lb/>
neglected to be an object of future care<lb/>
&amp; labour, unfinished not from a want<lb/>
of will in the Architect to pursue<lb/>
his object; but from a want of power.--<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
-- Electro-chemical Science relates to all<lb/>
the phenomena in which electrical agencies<lb/>
are concerned. -- It may be asked why<lb/>
has this new term been adopted? I trust<lb/>
not without good reasons - <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Electricity</hi> or<lb/>
Electrical Science has been always applied to<lb/>
a particular series of brilliant yet insulated<lb/>
effects in which chemical changes had<lb/>
no share -- The word <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#person_269"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag1" type="person">
          Galvanism
        </name>
            </rs> has<lb/>
likewise always been understood in a<lb/>
limited sense &amp; it could not with propriety<lb/>
be made to include a general view of<lb/>
corpuscular philosophy &amp; perhaps the<lb/>
name of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#person_269"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag2" type="person">
          Galvani
        </name>
            </rs> has been already too<lb/>
often associated with the later philosophical<lb/>
truths. This observer was indeed the fortunate<lb/>
&amp; accidental discoverer of a most important<lb/>
fact, but He mistook the interpretation &amp;<lb/>
pursued it to no extent. And it is to<lb/>
the penetrating Genius of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#person_199"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag3" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Volta</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> that we<lb/>
owe the most happy elucidations &amp; powerful<lb/>
instruments of the Science; but even the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
name of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#misc_228"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag4">
                  <hi rend="underline">Voltaism</hi>
               </term>
            </rs> could not be used<lb/>
with strict philosophical justice for his<lb/>
discoveries comprehended electrical phenomena<lb/>
alone, &amp; the most important results which<lb/>
have been since ascertained are chemical<lb/>
&amp; connected with the general system of<lb/>
operations in Art &amp; in Nature. -<lb/>
-- In so extensive a field of investigation<lb/>
a general view of the objects of discussion,<lb/>
of their order, connections &amp; applications<lb/>
cannot be improper - It will be tedious<lb/>
but it is necessary |_&amp; to all who may<lb/>
follow the course not merely from curiosity<lb/>
or the hope of being amused - but from<lb/>
the genuine love of knowledge I am<lb/>
convinced it will be useful. -<lb/>
Amidst the numerous subjects of exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">ts</hi>.<lb/>
you will find many that have been<lb/>
before introduced to you; yet the<lb/>
most interesting will be of a novel<lb/>
character : - You will find that<lb/>
something has been accomplished which<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
5I had ventured to hope for even within the<lb/>
short period that has elapsed since I last<lb/>
had the honour of addressing you - And<lb/>
it may be a source of gratification to know<lb/>
that this branch of Knowledge which you<lb/>
attended to &amp; fostered even in its infant<lb/>
state whilst helpless in <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">its</add> cradle has<lb/>
rapidly increased in strength &amp; power, &amp;<lb/>
has advanced, if not to the full form &amp;<lb/>
vigour of Manhood, at least to the<lb/>
freshness &amp; promise of Youth. -<lb/>
- Amidst the multifarious phenomenae<lb/>
of the external World, an immense number<lb/>
of similarities or analogies appear to the<lb/>
investigating mind - To arrange them &amp;<lb/>
to discover new ones by more minute observations,<lb/>
or experimental means is a principal business<lb/>
of Philosophy, &amp; the legitimate practise that<lb/>
sanctioned by the precepts of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#person_124"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag5" type="person">
          Bacon
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; the<lb/>
example of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="person">
          Newton
        </name>
            </rs> is to proceed from particular<lb/>
instances to general ones &amp; to found Hypotheses<lb/>
upon facts to be rejected or adopted<lb/>
Amidst the multifarious phenomena<lb/>
has advanced, if not to the full form &amp;<lb/>
rapidly increased in strength &amp; power, &amp;<lb/>
state whilst helpless in its cradle had<lb/>
attended to &amp; fostered even in its infant<lb/>
that this branch of Knowledge which you<lb/>
it may be a source of gratification to know<lb/>
had the honour of addressing you—And<lb/>
short period that has elapsed since I last<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
according as they are contradictory or comformable<lb/>
to new discoveries. -<lb/>
- I trust I shall be guided throughout<lb/>
the whole progress of enquiry by these principles<lb/>
 of research - |_ And in <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">employing</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">employing</add> them; |_ the first<lb/>
subject for discussion will be that which most<lb/>
applies &amp; which is most nearly related to<lb/>
the whole series of phenomena The subject<lb/>
of Electrical Attraction &amp; Repulsion. -<lb/>
- Certain bodies when heated or rubbed<lb/>
draw to them very light substances such as<lb/>
sealing wax or glass, which when thus<lb/>
excited attract feathers, bits of paper or<lb/>
Gold leaf; - This is remarkable but it is<lb/>
more remarkable that a light substance<lb/>
placed in a condition to be attracted by<lb/>
heated glass is driven away or repelled<lb/>
by heated sealing wax. -<lb/>
- It is on facts of this kind which<lb/>
may be almost infinitely multiplied - that<lb/>
the idea of positive &amp; negative Electricity<lb/>
has been established - It will not be<lb/>
necessary for us to discuss the remote cause<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
of the phaenomenon - Whether the attractions<lb/>
depend upon one very subtle fluid existing in<lb/>
the pores of all common bodies in larger or<lb/>
smaller quantities; or upon two etherial fluids<lb/>
capable as it were of neutralizing each other<lb/>
by combination, will be objects of enquiry for<lb/>
a more enlightened &amp; distant period of the<lb/>
Science which as yet is too immature to<lb/>
admit of generalizations even less refined<lb/>
- - The difference in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">electrical</hi> states of<lb/>
different Bodies, occasioned by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Heat</hi> or friction<lb/>
has long been known. - |_But that bodies existed<lb/>
naturally negative &amp; positive with regard to<lb/>
each other, independent of any mechanical or<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">late discovery.</hi>-<lb/>
A piece of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#chemical_201"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag7">
          Zinc
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; a piece of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag8">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs> when made<lb/>
to touch each other "&amp; separated are <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">found</add> by<lb/>
delicate tests the one negative the other positive<lb/>
A plate of glass made to touch a surface of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#chemical_033"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag9">
          quicksilver
          
        </term>
            </rs> is found positive &amp; the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#chemical_033"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag10">
          quicksilver
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
negative. -<lb/>
- - An immense number of similar instances<lb/>
exist. Whenever adequate means of investigation<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
have been employed, the phenomenon has<lb/>
been observed, &amp; it seems to apply to all<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">bodies differing in</hi> nature &amp; constitution. - - -<lb/>
- - The developement" of the Law &amp; the<lb/>
illustration of it by experiments must occupy<lb/>
much of our attention <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">from</hi> the importance<lb/>
of it in principle <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">&amp; from the</hi> extent of its<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">applications</hi> ,&amp; it will be found to offer<lb/>
explanations of a number of effects hitherto<lb/>
insulated or obscure. - - - -<lb/>
- - In the operation of common Electrical<lb/>
Machines the Electrical fluid has been<lb/>
generally conceived as pressed out of the<lb/>
glass by the influence of friction |_The<lb/>
theory, on the principle of natural electrical<lb/>
energy, will certainly be less complicated<lb/>
&amp; mechanical. - |_ Friction will be considered<lb/>
merely as a succession of contacts more<lb/>
effectually exhibiting what may be shewn<lb/>
even by a single contact, the natural<lb/>
positive <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">state of glass</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">with regard</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">to the</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">metallic amalgams</hi> or <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag11" ref="#misc_810" type="miscellaneous">
                  <term xml:id="tag11">
          silk
        </term>
               </rs> of the cushion</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
3<lb/>
- A plate of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#chemical_201"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag12">
          Zinc
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; a plate of Silver brought<lb/>
in contact with each other &amp; applied to the<lb/>
tongue produce a strong caustic sensation - |_ <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">This</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the experiment of <rs xml:id="ttag13" ref="#person_325" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag13" type="person">
          Sulzer
        </name>
               </rs>; &amp; the analogous</hi> exp<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">t</hi>..<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#person_269"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag14" type="person">
          Galvani
        </name>
            </rs> on the excitation of the muscles of<lb/>
animals, which for so long a time were supposed<lb/>
to be demonstrative of new <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">recondite</hi> principles<lb/>
intimately connected <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">with vitality in organic</hi>
            <lb/>
bodies, may be solved in the most perfect<lb/>
manner, according to the new elucidations, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">as</hi>
            <lb/>
simple facts of common electrical action. -<lb/>
- - In the grand arrangements of Nature with<lb/>
every alteration of place, with every new contact<lb/>
of Bodies, electrical effects must necessarily be<lb/>
connected, which require to be considered in<lb/>
examining the general laws of the changes &amp; trans =<lb/>
= mutations of matter. - The materials of the<lb/>
air, of the solid surface, &amp; of the Ocean differ<lb/>
in electrical energy - |_With all their mechanical<lb/>
movements in respect to each other there must<lb/>
be a disturbance of the electrical equilibrium<lb/>
&amp; on this idea may be explained <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">most</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">many</add> of the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
exhibitions of electrical effects constantly<lb/>
taking place in Nature which under common<lb/>
circumstances proceeding slowly &amp; gradually,<lb/>
are connected with the daily &amp; uniform<lb/>
order of events; but which in other cases<lb/>
appear to be the immediate or remote<lb/>
causes of remarkable &amp; awful phaenomena,<lb/>
&amp; associated with the whirlwind, the<lb/>
hurricanes &amp; the earthquake. - - -<lb/>
- - Excitation by contact seems to be <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxx</unclear>
            </del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">a great</add> cause of the common phaenomena of<lb/>
electrical attraction &amp; repulsion, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">but there</hi>
            <lb/>
is <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">another cause</hi>, in what is called the<lb/>
alteration of the electrical capacity of Bodies<lb/>
in consequence of alterations in their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">specific</hi>
            <lb/>
forms or composition . - |_ <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Bodies</hi> expanding<lb/>
enlarging in their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">dimensions</hi> from the influence<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">heat</hi>, become negative, - Bodies contracting,<lb/>
suffering a diminution of volume by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">cooling</hi>
            <lb/>
on the contrary are <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">positive</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">&amp; as it were</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">communicate</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">electricity</hi> to the surrounding<lb/>
bodies, whatever may be their natural<lb/>
energies. - -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
- Thus water thrown upon a red hot plate<lb/>
of Silver is expanded to many hundred times<lb/>
its former volume; &amp; it rendered the silver<lb/>
negative - But steam thrown upon a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">cold</hi>
            <lb/>
plate of Silver so as to be condensed into water<lb/>
makes it positive -<lb/>
- In considering the common &amp; artificial<lb/>
phaenomena of electricity we shall often have<lb/>
occasion to recur to the principle of the changes<lb/>
of chemical capacity; |_For in processes of friction<lb/>
the heat produced often alters the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">capacities</hi>
            <lb/>
of the acting substances unequally, &amp; hence<lb/>
modifies the results which would arise from<lb/>
the pure exhibition of their electrical energies -<lb/>
|_ In natural phaenomena this law of capacity<lb/>
acts a still more important part. -<lb/>
- By Evaporation, from the diffusion of water<lb/>
in air, the surface is rendered negative &amp;<lb/>
by the condensation of moisture in the upper<lb/>
regions of the Atmosphere its strata become<lb/>
positive, &amp; water being a conducting substance<lb/>
clouds are changed, &amp; in returning their contents<lb/>
to the sources whence they sprang; they<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
moisten the earth in Rain, dew, or mist<lb/>
&amp; occasion lightning &amp; thunder. - - -<lb/>
-- |_ These facts of electrical excitement are<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primary</hi>; but there are others which though<lb/>
secondary will require an attentive inves-<lb/>
-tigation those connected with what is<lb/>
called <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">propogated</hi> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">induced</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Electricity</hi>. - -<lb/>
- - - Different Bodies possess very<lb/>
different powers with regard to electrical<lb/>
transfer or communication -- some are said<lb/>
to be perfect conductors, such as metals<lb/>
that is to say the electrical influence<lb/>
rapidly pervades their parts, others are<lb/>
imperfect conductors which as it were<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">expose obstacles</hi> to its passage, such is water<lb/>
which according to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#person_026"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag15" type="person">
          M<hi rend="superscript">
                     <hi rend="underline">r</hi>
                  </hi> Cavendish's
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
computation conducts 400. 000, 000 less<lb/>
perfectly than Iron. - -  Others again<lb/>
are non conductors such as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">glass</hi>, being<lb/>
impermeable to Electricity. - - - |_ Even<lb/>
amongst conductors, there are great<lb/>
differences in their relations to the<lb/>
different states of electrical excitement,<lb/>
thus some conduct negative electricity only<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="13"
                xml:id="pb-13"
                facs="#i13"/>
            <lb/>
4<lb/>
as soap, &amp; others positive Electricity only as the<lb/>
flame of a candle. |_&amp; these remarkable powers<lb/>
established by the late researches of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#person_317"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag16" type="person">
          Erman
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
will be found to lead to important conclusions<lb/>
&amp; in some measure to connect the mechanical<lb/>
&amp; chemical properties of matter.<lb/>
- A Body positively electrified rendered<lb/>
another Body in its vicinity negative &amp;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">vice versa. A Body negatively electrified</hi>
            <lb/>
renders some contiguous body positive. |_&amp; if<lb/>
the Electricities are exalted a discharge results.<lb/>
This is the fact of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">induction</hi>, of which a<lb/>
number of elucidations will be offered to you.-<lb/>
- It is on this principle that the transfer<lb/>
of electricity in the common electrical machine<lb/>
from the Glass, to the conductor, is performed.-<lb/>
&amp; on this depends the operation of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#misc_130"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag17">
          Leyden<lb/>jar
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; the battery by which an immense<lb/>
accumulation of Electricity is produced &amp;<lb/>
some of the great effects in Nature imitated.-<lb/>
|_ - Conductors for preserving buildings from<lb/>
the effects of lightning and upon the principle<lb/>
of being induced into an opposite state from<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="14"
                xml:id="pb-14"
                facs="#i14"/>
            <lb/>
that of the cloud or the atmosphere &amp;<lb/>
presenting points only they occasion &amp;<lb/>
slow discharge of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Electricity</hi> &amp; disperse<lb/>
this <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">active</hi> &amp; often <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">terrible</hi> agent in<lb/>
harmless &amp; beautiful flashes. - - -<lb/>
- - Clouds when charged with negative<lb/>
electricity induce positive Electricity upon<lb/>
other clouds in their neighbourhood. -<lb/>
&amp; these again occasion the opposite state<lb/>
in some other contiguous matter; &amp; hence<lb/>
by an alternation of circumstances &amp;<lb/>
a communication with the surface of the<lb/>
earth the equilibrium is gradually restored. -<lb/>
- - |_ It is in the law of induction combined<lb/>
with the general property of electrical<lb/>
energy, that the powers of the most<lb/>
wonderful &amp; important <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">electrical</add> instrument<lb/>
ever discovered depends - You must<lb/>
perceive that I mean what has<lb/>
been called the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#person_269"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag18" type="person">
          Galvanic battery
        </name>
            </rs> or<lb/>
the apparatus of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag19"
                ref="#person_199"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag19" type="person">
          Volta
        </name>
            </rs>. - - - -<lb/>
- - I have mentioned that a piece<lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#chemical_201"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag20">
          Zinc
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag21"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag21">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs> when brought in<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="15"
                xml:id="pb-15"
                facs="#i15"/>
            <lb/>
contact are in the relations of negative<lb/>
&amp; positive; &amp; when many series of this kind<lb/>
are constructed with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water or an</hi> imperfect<lb/>
fluid <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">conductor interposed</hi>; - The electrical<lb/>
power increases in an uniform ratio with<lb/>
the number - negative electricity being induced<lb/>
upon every plate naturally negative &amp;<lb/>
positive electricity upon every plate naturally<lb/>
positive. - - - -<lb/>
- - The construction of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag22"
                ref="#chemical_161"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag22">
          Voltaic
          
        </term>
            </rs> instrument,<lb/>
its agencies, &amp; the theory of its operation<lb/>
will be demonstrated upon an extensive<lb/>
sca<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">v</hi>le. - The Battery before you, is a<lb/>
small part of a series consisting of 600<lb/>
plates of the same size, a combination<lb/>
at least four times as powerful as any<lb/>
that has been <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">hitherto</add> constructed. - - -<lb/>
- - Whatever is brilliant or impressive<lb/>
in the experiments made in this course<lb/>
of lectures; will be owing to the agencies<lb/>
of this instrument; but it has been<lb/>
provided not so much for the purpose of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="16"
                xml:id="pb-16"
                facs="#i16"/>
            <lb/>
exhibiting what is already known. What<lb/>
might be accomplished by more simple<lb/>
means, as for the<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline"> end of</hi> new research<lb/>
&amp; with the hope of new discovery. ---<lb/>
-- I trust you will not consider me<lb/>
as activated by any sentiment of vanity<lb/>
when I say that the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag23"
                ref="#chemical_161"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag23">
          Voltaic
          
        </term>
            </rs> combination<lb/>
will be presented to you in these lectures<lb/>
under a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">new</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">novel</add> point of view; as offering<lb/>
the most efficient means of producing<lb/>
new changes, as being the most powerful<lb/>
agent that has yet been discovered for<lb/>
effecting decomposition &amp; new combinations<lb/>
&amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in this respect</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">thus</add> superseding most of the<lb/>
common chemical powers. - - - -<lb/>
-- - In this it will be seen that<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#person_199"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag24" type="person">
          Volta
        </name>
            </rs> has presented to us a Key<lb/>
which promises to lay open <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxx</unclear>
            </del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">some</add>
            <lb/>
of the most mysterious recesses of Nature. -<lb/>
- till this discovery our <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">powers</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">means</add> were<lb/>
limited, the field of pneumatic research<lb/>
had been exhausted &amp; little remained<lb/>
for the experimentalist except laborious<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="17"
                xml:id="pb-17"
                facs="#i17"/>
            <lb/>
5<lb/>
&amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">minute</hi> processes - |_There is now before<lb/>
us, a boundless prospect of novelty in<lb/>
Science; a Country unexplored, but<lb/>
noble &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">fertile</hi> in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">aspect</hi> a land of<lb/>
promise in Philosophy. -<lb/>
- After having considered the physical<lb/>
powers &amp; Laws of Electricity &amp; the<lb/>
combinations invented for exhibiting its<lb/>
properties - The next object will be the<lb/>
discussion of its relations to the general<lb/>
chemical operations of matter | &amp; this enquiry<lb/>
will naturally follow the History of the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#chemical_161"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag25">
          Voltaic
          
        </term>
            </rs> Battery &amp; will be copious in facts,<lb/>
instances &amp; inductions. -<lb/>
[X]|_ - - That Bodies differing in Nature blend<lb/>
or unite with each other into a common mass<lb/>
possessed of new properties is the most simple<lb/>
&amp; ancient fact of chemical affinity; But<lb/>
that all bodies which have been accurately<lb/>
examined so combining or blending, are possessed<lb/>
of opposite electrical energies was for the first<lb/>
time made publicly known in the course of the<lb/>
last year. - - - - - [/X]<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="18"
                xml:id="pb-18"
                facs="#i18"/>
            <lb/>
- Bodies possessed of similar electrical<lb/>
energies according to the common laws of<lb/>
electrical attraction &amp; repulsion ought<lb/>
to repel each other - Bodies possessed<lb/>
of different electrical energies ought to<lb/>
attract each other. - |_The question may be<lb/>
asked then? - is not what has been always<lb/>
called chemical affinity merely the<lb/>
union or coalescence, of particles naturally<lb/>
in opposite electrical states? - &amp; are<lb/>
not the chemical attractions of particles<lb/>
&amp; the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">electrical</hi> attractions of masses<lb/>
owing to one property &amp; governed by<lb/>
one simple law. - - -.<lb/>
- - There are extensive series of<lb/>
phaenomena which favour this idea<lb/>
&amp; as yet no contradictory fact has<lb/>
occurred <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to me</del>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">&amp; the</hi> Electrical &amp;<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">chemical functions of</hi> Bodies as far<lb/>
as our knowledge extends - exist only<lb/>
together &amp; are modified, created,<lb/>
or destroyed at the same time. - -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="19"
                xml:id="pb-19"
                facs="#i19"/>
            <lb/>
- Thus a metal is naturally positive with<lb/>
regard to <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag26"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag26">
          oxygen
          
        </term>
            </rs>, when this its electricity<lb/>
is increased it combines with <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag27">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>, with<lb/>
more facility; but if it is made negative<lb/>
it refuses to combine or remain in union -<lb/>
&amp; repulsion instead of attraction takes place. -<lb/>
-Acids in general again are negative,<lb/>
Alkalies, earths &amp; metallic oxides positive; -<lb/>
&amp; as is well known they unite to form<lb/>
new compounds; - But if an acid be<lb/>
made positive by artificial means, it refuses<lb/>
to combine with alkalies or if alkalies be<lb/>
made negative, they will no longer act upon<lb/>
acids;. &amp; by employing different electricities,)<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in consequence</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">these effects neutral</hi> salts &amp;<lb/>
an immense number of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">other compounds</hi>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">may</hi>
            <lb/>
be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">decomposed</hi> &amp; their elements obtained.-<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">- - The probability of this idea is evident;</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">but in the present state of our knowledge</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">it would be premature to erect it into</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a Theory:- New arrangements of facts</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">opposed to it may be discovered, at a</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="20"
                xml:id="pb-20"
                facs="#i20"/>
            <lb/>
future period; It is a conjecture;<lb/>
but I trust not a vague one. it has<lb/>
opened a path of discovery |_&amp; as far<lb/>
as it has been applied has performed<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">more</hi> even than it promised. -<lb/>
- Whatever be the fate of the opinion<lb/>
that electrical energy &amp; chemical<lb/>
Attraction are one &amp; the same power -<lb/>
The facts of the dependence of the<lb/>
chemical arrangements of matter<lb/>
upon Electrical functions will be<lb/>
permanent, &amp; will be found to offer<lb/>
adequate &amp; simple methods for<lb/>
determining the Nature &amp; species of<lb/>
bodies &amp; the most refined &amp; exalted<lb/>
power of analysis. - - - - -<lb/>
- - Bodies found on chemical examination<lb/>
to consist either wholly or principally<lb/>
of inflammable matter are naturally<lb/>
highly positive - Bodies on the contrary<lb/>
consisting either entirely or chiefly of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="21"
                xml:id="pb-21"
                facs="#i21"/>
            <lb/>
21<lb/>
matter capable of supporting combustion are<lb/>
naturally negative ; &amp; where <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the two electrical</hi>
            <lb/>
powers are artificially exhibited in the<lb/>
same system of Bodies, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag28">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; such<lb/>
substances as contain <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag29"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag29">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs> in excess, are<lb/>
uniformly brought into a state of rest in<lb/>
the sphere of positive electricity; &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag30"
                ref="#chemical_007"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag30">
          Hydrogene
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag31"
                ref="#chemical_037"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag31">
          Sulphur
          
        </term>
            </rs>, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag32"
                ref="#chemical_151"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag32">
          phosphorus
          
        </term>
            </rs>, metals in short<lb/>
combustible bodies in general are repelled<lb/>
from the sphere of positive electricity &amp;<lb/>
attracted into that of negative Electricity.<lb/>
|_ Metallic oxides, earths &amp; alkalies are<lb/>
all positive &amp; are attracted by negatively<lb/>
electrified surfaces - |_but metallic oxides<lb/>
consist of a large portion of different in=<lb/>
=flammable matters combined with a small<lb/>
proportion of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag33"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag33">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>; - Analogy induced<lb/>
me to believe that the alkalies &amp; earths<lb/>
were similar compounds; &amp; experiments<lb/>
as far as they have gone, have converted<lb/>
this conjecture into a truth. ----<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="22"
                xml:id="pb-22"
                facs="#i22"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">-- The alkalies &amp; such of the Earths</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">as it has been my good fortune to</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">decompose are constituted as I had</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">suspected by <rs xml:id="ttag34" ref="#chemical_022" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag34">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
               </rs> &amp; highly inflam=</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">=mable bases - the last in excess &amp;</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">these <hi rend="underline">new bases</hi> present an assemblage</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of most extraordinary physical &amp;</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">chemical properties: -</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <hi rend="underline">Space</hi> - The bases of the alkalies agree</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">with metals in all sensible <del rend="strikethrough">properties</del>
               <add>qualities</add>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">except weight, they are lighter than</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">water &amp; one of them is the lightest</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <add>solid</add> fluid known to exist. - Such is their</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">attraction for <rs xml:id="ttag35" ref="#chemical_022" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag35">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
               </rs> that they separate</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">it from all its combinations that</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">have been tried; &amp; the basis of</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <rs xml:id="ttag36" ref="#chemical_030" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag36">
          potash
          
        </term>
               </rs> burns spontaneously on the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">contact of ice or waters. -</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">- |_ The same system of reasoning</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which led to the suspicion &amp; discovery</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of an excess of inflammable matter in</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">alkalies &amp; earths must likewise</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="23"
                xml:id="pb-23"
                facs="#i23"/>
            <lb/>
induce us to believe that the undecompounded<lb/>
acids consist of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag37"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag37">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs> in large &amp; combustible<lb/>
matters in small proportions |_&amp; this seems<lb/>
to be the fact with the only one that<lb/>
I have yet been able to experiment upon<lb/>
the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag38"
                ref="#chemical_041"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag38">
          boracic acid
          
        </term>
            </rs>. -<lb/>
- In these developments of new elements<lb/>
new instruments of research are continually<lb/>
produced, their scientific applications are<lb/>
almost boundless &amp; the power of electrical<lb/>
decomposition will probably exhibit to us<lb/>
all the elements of matter possessing the<lb/>
functions of positive &amp; negative, of burning,<lb/>
&amp; of supporting combustion. -<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">- - After having classed the simple or</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">undecompounded principles <del rend="strikethrough">examined</del>
               <del rend="strikethrough">considered</del>
               <add>examined</add> the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">primary compounds that they form by</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">union with each other &amp; <del rend="strikethrough">examined</del>
               <add>demonstrated</add> their</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">properties by experiments - The following</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">lectures will be devoted to the consideration</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of the Bodies formed by more complicated</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">means - the combinations of Acids, alkalies,</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="24"
                xml:id="pb-24"
                facs="#i24"/>
            <lb/>
oxides, &amp; salts. - - - .<lb/>
-- Even on this subject we shall<lb/>
be still guided to a certain extent<lb/>
by the electrical character - &amp; the<lb/>
power of union will be found to be<lb/>
indicated by the energies of the known<lb/>
elements. -----<lb/>
- Salts containing an excess of acid<lb/>
are negative - those containing an<lb/>
excess of alkali or earth are positive,<lb/>
&amp; in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">perfectly neutral</hi> compounds<lb/>
the electricity appears by common<lb/>
tests, in perfect equilibrium in a state<lb/>
of perfect repose - - -<lb/>
- - The Energy of combination belongs<lb/>
in the highest degree to simple bodies<lb/>
- &amp; it almost disappears in very complex<lb/>
substances &amp; this law is immediately<lb/>
subservient to the perfection of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">arrangements of matter</hi>, in living organs. -<lb/>
- - The elements of the Atmosphere<lb/>
the ocean &amp; the solid parts of the Earth<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="25"
                xml:id="pb-25"
                facs="#i25"/>
            <lb/>
7<lb/>
are constantly acting upon each other so as<lb/>
to produce combinations fitted for the<lb/>
ends of life. - Vegetables, by assimilating<lb/>
water. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag39"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag39">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>, &amp; inflammable principles<lb/>
existing in the soil, form materials for a<lb/>
more perfect structure adapted to resist<lb/>
the common destructive powers of Nature.<lb/>
By mechanical agencies matter is divided<lb/>
so as to be susceptible of the operation of<lb/>
chemical laws, &amp; by chemical laws, it is<lb/>
combined for the purposes of animation,<lb/>
its ultimate &amp; highest destination. -<lb/>
- |_It has been <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">X</hi> conjectured that some<lb/>
even of the functions of living Beings depend<lb/>
upon electrical changes; &amp; the facts of the<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag40"
                ref="#person_269"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag40" type="person">
          Galvanic
        </name>
            </rs> excitation of muscles <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">after</hi> the<lb/>
death of animals has led to the idea.-<lb/>
- This subject will be considered &amp;<lb/>
though it cannot be much <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">enlightened</hi>
            <lb/>
by our existing knowledge - yet this<lb/>
knowledge will be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sufficient</hi> to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">overturn</hi>
            <lb/>
some of the bold Hypotheses which<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
have been attached to it. ---<lb/>
-- Physiology is as yet the most<lb/>
independent &amp; least advanced of the<lb/>
Sciences - |_It unfolds to us the most<lb/>
admirable <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects</hi>; but we are unable<lb/>
to trace their <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">causes</hi>. - |_In referring<lb/>
muscular contraction to electrical<lb/>
changes we do not advance a step -<lb/>
it is mere <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">conjecture</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">supposition -</add> - Electricity<lb/>
most probably acts as a stimulus<lb/>
alone in common experiments. - And<lb/>
the only electrical arrangements known<lb/>
,in animal structures, those of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag41"
                ref="#misc_233"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag41">
          Torpedo
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag42"
                ref="#misc_232"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag42">
          gymnotus
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; other fishes are not<lb/>
organs of vitality but instruments<lb/>
of attack or defence. ---<lb/>
-- |_When the grand discoveries of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag43"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag43" type="person">
          Newton
        </name>
            </rs> were first developed, it was<lb/>
the fashion amongst speculators to refer<lb/>
muscular motion &amp; the motive powers<lb/>
of animals to mechanical causes; &amp;<lb/>
&amp; springs &amp; elastic globules were<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
the machinery imagined. ----<lb/>
-- With the pneumatic Chemistry arose<lb/>
the pneumatic physiology when <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag44"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag44">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag45"
                ref="#chemical_007"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag45">
          Hydrogene
          
        </term>
            </rs>, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag46"
                ref="#chemical_017"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag46">
          Azote
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag47"
                ref="#chemical_054"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag47">
          Carbon
          
        </term>
            </rs> became the<lb/>
supposed energetic agents in living Natures.-<lb/>
--- The experiments of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag48"
                ref="#person_269"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag48" type="person">
          Galvani
        </name>
            </rs> introduced<lb/>
positive &amp; negative electricity, &amp; the idea<lb/>
of muscles &amp; nerves operating on the principle<lb/>
of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag49"
                ref="#misc_130"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag49">
          Leyden Phial
        </term>
            </rs>. --<lb/>
- Most of these dreams have long ago<lb/>
passed away- All of them will pass<lb/>
away. -- Life appears to us through<lb/>
sensible phaenomena; but the powers<lb/>
concerned in its operations must for ever<lb/>
be hidden. - To apply the laws of<lb/>
common matter to organised structures is<lb/>
seeking the living amongst the dead -<lb/>
looking for the ruler amidst slaves -<lb/>
That which sees will not be visible;<lb/>
- that which touches us will not be felt;<lb/>
that which <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">commands</hi> sensations will<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
not be their subject. ---<lb/>
-- The lectures will be concluded<lb/>
with an outline of the History of<lb/>
the Science - In this I shall have<lb/>
an opportunity of recapitulating<lb/>
the principal facts of the course -<lb/>
of referring them to their inventors<lb/>
&amp; of considering them in their relations<lb/>
to human talent &amp; ingenuity. ---<lb/>
Little space - <lb/>
Such is the plan which I shall<lb/>
attempt to execute; such the nature of<lb/>
the information which I shall lay before<lb/>
you -- |_Having developed <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">my objects</hi>
            <lb/>
it will be improper for me, to say much<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">advantages</hi> that may be derived<lb/>
from this kind of study - You must<lb/>
already have weighed them &amp; it is<lb/>
not my wish to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">entice</hi> you to follow<lb/>
the course, for I should constantly<lb/>
dread the uneasy feeling of disappointing<lb/>
you. - - - - -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
8<lb/>
- The path of Physical discovery so delightful<lb/>
to Inventors usually appears rough &amp; dis=<lb/>
=agreeable, to general enquirers. - It is a<lb/>
way amongst mountains offering Sublime<lb/>
views - but difficult to the traveller. --<lb/>
- - Of all subjects however that of<lb/>
experimental enquiry demands most to be<lb/>
brought forward in public lectures - It requires<lb/>
the evidence of the senses - &amp; the methods<lb/>
used can only be understood, by being<lb/>
exhibited.- The seed should be spread<lb/>
abroad &amp; if in a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">few instances</hi> only, it falls<lb/>
on a fertile soil, the end is accomplished.-<lb/>
-- |_ In this advanced age of the world<lb/>
there ought to be no question concerning<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">importance</hi> of Natural knowledge<lb/>
of discoveries of the powers of Nature &amp;<lb/>
of the wise laws by which they are<lb/>
governed. -<lb/>
- - It does however sometimes occur<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">that the enquiry is</hi> made, Of what use<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
is this knowledge? Of what use<lb/>
is that discovery? &amp; the word<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">use</hi> employed in this way, always<lb/>
means some vulgar or immediate<lb/>
application, something connected<lb/>
with our common wants. -<lb/>
- I do not mean to insinuate<lb/>
that even this kind of use should<lb/>
be neglected in research |_&amp; indeed<lb/>
it has generally happened "that<lb/>
great philosophical discoveries have<lb/>
been accompanied by noble practical<lb/>
&amp; popular applications - I mean<lb/>
merely to argue <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">only</del>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">against too</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great an extension of</hi> the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">feeling</hi>
            <lb/>
against an <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">extension of it which</hi> makes<lb/>
Truth &amp; Wisdom &amp; Knowledge<lb/>
of no importance for their own sakes. -<lb/>
- <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">It has been a common place</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Saying " that the person who causes</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">two blades of corn to grow where one</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">only grew before is a greater Benefactor</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">to Society than the Author of the</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">greatest philosophical discovery</del>
            <lb/>
- |_If there be any thing dignified or noble<lb/>
or worthy of estimation belonging to Humanity<lb/>
any thing superior to the common sentiment<lb/>
of self love, it appears in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">those faculties</hi>
            <lb/>
by which we endeavour to exalt &amp; sublime<lb/>
our intellectual nature &amp; to gain a<lb/>
dominion over the senses |_&amp; after our<lb/>
sacred &amp; moral duties, there is no pursuit<lb/>
more worthy of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">attention</hi> than that which<lb/>
unfolds to us the infinitely wise &amp; wonderful<lb/>
mechanism of Nature, &amp; which produces<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">benefits</hi> from the hidden properties of things,<lb/>
ordained in their diversified relations for<lb/>
the pleasure &amp; advantage of Man. -<lb/>
- If an objection be made to any of<lb/>
the truths of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Experimental Science</hi> from<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="32"
                xml:id="pb-32"
                facs="#i32"/>
            <lb/>
their want of popular application -<lb/>
how much more will such reasoning<lb/>
apply to Letters in general, to Poetry<lb/>
&amp; the fine Arts <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">&amp; to those things which ornament &amp; <unclear>xxxxxxxx</unclear> social life</add> yet in this case<lb/>
it would be more generally found<lb/>
ridiculous because the taste for them<lb/>
is more diffused &amp; more fashionable -<lb/>
&amp; were any one to ask what has<lb/>
been the use of a sublime poem,<lb/>
or a beautiful picture or statue<lb/>
he would not be thought deserving<lb/>
of an answer. - - -<lb/>
- - Human Beings have been created<lb/>
for happiness &amp; a principal means<lb/>
of obtaining it is by the exercise<lb/>
of the intellectual faculties, by<lb/>
an exertion of Reason &amp; imagination,<lb/>
by imitating Nature &amp; modifying her<lb/>
operations. |_&amp; Knowledge is no less<lb/>
necessary to supply the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">wants</hi> of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="33"
                xml:id="pb-33"
                facs="#i33"/>
            <lb/>
9<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the mind</hi> than food is to support the functions<lb/>
of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Body</hi>. -<lb/>
- |_If we argue against any species of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">true</hi>
            <lb/>
improvement, we argue for the uncultivated<lb/>
against the civilized condition - for who shall<lb/>
assign the limits where utility begins &amp; ends;-<lb/>
The savage would consider as useful only, what<lb/>
procured food &amp; shelter. -, The civilized Man<lb/>
extends the term to the comforts, refinements,<lb/>
&amp; even luxuries, of life; - By the enlightened<lb/>
mind all these are considered as of importance<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">but</hi> he will place the sources of intellectual<lb/>
pleasure above them all. -<lb/>
- The defence of the Sciences has been so<lb/>
admirably executed by the same great mind<lb/>
which in modern times fixed their foundations;<lb/>
that I cannot avoid giving a few sentences<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">from his works, on the subject.-</hi>
            <lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
- "The introduction of noble discoveries,"<lb/>
says our Author, "seems to hold by far<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="34"
                xml:id="pb-34"
                facs="#i34"/>
            <lb/>
the most excellent place among all<lb/>
human actions | &amp; this was the judgment<lb/>
of antiquity which attributed <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">divine</hi>
            <lb/>
honours to inventors but conferred<lb/>
only <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">heroical</hi> honours on those who<lb/>
deserved well of their Country in civil<lb/>
affairs - And whoever rightly considers<lb/>
will find this a judicious custom |_ for<lb/>
the merit of civil benefits is confined<lb/>
within the circle of an age or nation -;<lb/>
&amp; is like a fruitful shower which<lb/>
though profitable &amp; good serves only<lb/>
for a season &amp; fertilizes a single spot;-<lb/>
- But discoveries are like blessings of<lb/>
Heaven permanent &amp; universal<lb/>
applying to all <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ages &amp; all conditions</hi>
            <lb/>
of Society. - - |_ <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag50"
                ref="#otherwork_179"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag50">
            And to leave the vulgar<lb/>arguments that by knowledge Man<lb/>excelleth Man
        </bibl>
            </rs> in that in which<lb/>
man excelleth Beasts - that by learning<lb/>
Man ascendeth to the Heavens &amp; their<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="35"
                xml:id="pb-35"
                facs="#i35"/>
            <lb/>
motions where in Body he cannot come &amp; the<lb/>
like, let us consider the dignity &amp; excellence<lb/>
of Knowledge in that to which Human Nature<lb/>
most aspires which is immortality or continuance.<lb/>
For to this tends the raising of houses &amp; families.<lb/>
to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">this, buildings</hi>, foundations &amp; monuments.<lb/>
&amp; the desire <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of memory</hi> fame &amp; celebration -<lb/>
|_But the monuments of invention &amp; learning<lb/>
are far more durable than the monuments<lb/>
of power or the work of the most skilful<lb/>
hands, for the first decay &amp; are injured<lb/>
or destroyed but the last remain &amp; are<lb/>
perpetuated by letters exempted from the<lb/>
wrongs of time or capable of perfect<lb/>
renovation". -<lb/>
- In this eulogium the illustrious Author<lb/>
has alluded to knowledge &amp; invention in<lb/>
general; but it may be particularly said<lb/>
of discoveries in experimental philosophy<lb/>
that they cannot but produce benefits &amp;<lb/>
can by no means be turned to evil or unworthy<lb/>
purposes. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="36"
                xml:id="pb-36"
                facs="#i36"/>
            <lb/>
- - Literature &amp; the refined Arts though<lb/>
most noble in their general effects may be<lb/>
misapplied. - Natural Science on the<lb/>
contrary being an exhibition of the powers<lb/>
existing in the Universe of things cannot<lb/>
be subservient to the passions, prejudices,<lb/>
or vices of Men. - As far as it influences<lb/>
the mind it must correct all evil tendencies<lb/>
&amp; having a sublime origin in philosophical<lb/>
minds it descends even to the most familiar<lb/>
offices &amp; is subservient to common purposes.-<lb/>
Like a stream rising amongst mountains, it<lb/>
flows from the heavens to the earth - &amp; though<lb/>
in its begin<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">n</del>ings it is known only to a<lb/>
few, its benefits gradually extend, &amp;<lb/>
it at length adorns &amp; fertilizes an<lb/>
extensive &amp; populous district. - - -<lb/>
[Ink squiggle flourish]<lb/>
            <lb/>
         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
</TEI>
